  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Inscription on Maechen with Preface
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The hamlet where Ha Ho-bo makes his dwelling is called Maechen. He has taken this as his pen name. He has requested an inscription from me many times. I have respectfully composed this inscription:

    The inscription says:
    How fair, that plum tree there,
    With waters winding round its roots.
    Though dust and grime are kept at bay,
    Nature's own buds form in silence.
    Through jade-framed windows, moonlight falls so white,
    Snow-laden plums herald the spring.
    Who could match such virtue?
    I long for one with such a heart.
  footnotes:
    - Maechen (梅川) literally means 'Plum Stream,' combining the characters for plum and water.
    - The plum tree (mei) serves as a traditional symbol of integrity and refinement in East Asian poetry, often representing the scholar-gentleman.
    - The 'jade-framed windows' evoke the refined domestic space and cultivated aesthetic sensibility of the subject.
